\f1\b \cf2 \strokec4 What this actually provides \'97 in plain language:
\f0\b0 \cf2 \strokec4 \
At the core, Aperture answers three questions that nobody else can answer systematically:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl0
\f1\b \cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	1	}\cf2 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec4 "Which companies are gaining traction with the government?"
\f0\b0 \cf2 \strokec4  \'97 The signal detection layer watches for SBIR phase transitions, contract velocity, multi-agency interest, and outsized awards. The composite scoring ranks them. The snapshots track how those scores change over time.\
\ls1\ilvl0
\f1\b \cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	2	}\cf2 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec4 "When is a defense company ready to raise, and from whom?"
\f0\b0 \cf2 \strokec4  \'97 The comparables engine benchmarks any company against ~100 peers on timing (months from Phase II to first raise), capital amounts (median/mean at each stage), and SBIR depth at raise. The investor network graph maps who's been writing checks in adjacent thesis areas via Form D director data.\
\ls1\ilvl0
\f1\b \cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	3	}\cf2 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec4 "Where is government policy creating tailwinds?"
\f0\b0 \cf2 \strokec4  \'97 The policy alignment layer maps each company to 10 budget priority areas with real FY growth rates. A company aligned to space resilience (+38%) tells a different story than one aligned to hypersonics (-43%).\
