\f1\b \cf2 \strokec4 Where the value compounds:
\f0\b0 \cf2 \strokec4 \
The defensibility layers you just built are what make this a data 
\f2\i \cf2 \strokec4 asset
\f0\i0 \cf2 \strokec4  rather than just a tool. Every day the snapshots run, you get trajectory data no one else has. Every entity resolution correction improves matching accuracy. Every report delivery + feedback cycle validates or invalidates your signal definitions. Every enrichment finding closes a gap permanently \'97 not just for one report, but for every future query against that entity.\

\f1\b \cf2 \strokec4 The honest gaps right now:
\f0\b0 \cf2 \strokec4 \
The biggest are the ones you're closing: OTA contracts and complete funding round sizes. Without those, your lifecycle classification underestimates companies (X-Bow showing "Prototype" when they're in production) and your government traction section has blind spots on exactly the contract types that matter most for defense startups.\
The second gap is coverage breadth on the entity side. You mentioned the data quality issue where semantic search matches keywords without understanding business models. Your entity classification confidence scores help, but there's likely still noise in the entity set that affects comparables quality.\
The third gap is the feedback loop \'97 it's instrumented now but empty. You need deliveries and outcomes to start flowing through it before you can credibly say "our signals have a validated hit rate."\

\f1\b \cf2 \strokec4 The strategic picture:
\f0\b0 \cf2 \strokec4 \
What you've built is a vertical intelligence infrastructure for defense private markets. The moat is the combination of fragmented data sources unified through entity resolution, proprietary signal definitions, and temporal trajectory data that compounds daily. No one can replicate this by prompting an LLM because the data infrastructure underneath doesn't exist anywhere else in assembled form.\
The question is whether you monetize it as a platform (subscriptions for ongoing access), a service (reports on demand), or a fund edge (use it to invest). Those are very different businesses, but the underlying asset is the same.\
